\begin_layout FrameSubtitle
Conditional probability of events
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Probability theory models the way we should measure uncertainty.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
When we run a random experiment we only know that the outcome will belong
 to the sample space 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 According to this information (no information) we have a probability space
 and a law 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 wich assigns probabilities to events: 
\begin_inset Formula $(S,\mathcal{G},P)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
What happens to these probabilities if we acquire new information about
 the outcome of the experiment?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Suppose that we don't observe the outcome of the experiment but we know
 that 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in B\in\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 the event 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is realised.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Then, what is the probability of event 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 given that event 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is realised (we simply say 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

given 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

), denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $P(A\mid B)$
\end_inset

?
\end_layout

\begin_layout EndFrame

\end_layout

\begin_layout BeginFrame
Conditional probability
\end_layout

\begin_layout FrameSubtitle
Conditional probability of events
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Assume 
\begin_inset Formula $B\in\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $P(B)\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 The conditional probability of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 given 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\dots$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $P(B\mid B)=1.$
\end_inset

 There is no uncertainty regarding the realisation of event 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 once we know it is realised.
 We have 
\emph on
normalized
\emph default
 the probability of event 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 such that now it is equal to 1.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is finite and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G=P}(S)$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $P(B)\neq0$
\end_inset

 it makes then sense to define for all 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in S$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P(\{s\}\mid B)=\begin{cases}
\frac{P(\{s\})}{P(B)} & s\in B\\
0 & s\notin B
\end{cases}.
\]

\end_inset

In fact, recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $B=\bigcup_{s\in B}\{s\}$
\end_inset

 and from axiom 2 of a (conditional) probability law 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P(B\mid B)=P(\bigcup_{s\in B}\{s\}\mid B)=\sum_{s\in B}P(\{s\}\mid B)=\sum_{s\in B}\frac{P(\{s\})}{P(B)}=\frac{P(B)}{P(B)}=1.
\]

\end_inset

For any 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $A=(A\setminus B)\cup(A\cap B).$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout EndFrame

\end_layout

\begin_layout BeginFrame
Conditional probability
\end_layout

\begin_layout FrameSubtitle
Conditional probability of events
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(continued)
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
P(A\mid B) & = & \sum_{s\in A}P(\{s\}\mid B)\\
 & = & \sum_{s\in A\setminus B}P(\{s\}\mid B)+\sum_{s\in A\cap B}P(\{s\}\mid B)\\
 & = & 0+\sum_{s\in A\cap B}\frac{P(\{s\})}{P(B)}\\
 & = & P(A\cap B)/P(B)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
All sample points not in 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 can be disregarded because the outcome of the experiment must be in 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 For each event 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 the relevant sample points are those common with 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 the points in 
\begin_inset Formula $A\cap B$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout EndFrame

\end_layout

\begin_layout BeginFrame
Conditional probability
\end_layout

\begin_layout FrameSubtitle
Conditional probability of events
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
The conditional probability of event 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 given event 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is therefore defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P(A\mid B)=\begin{cases}
\frac{P(A\cap B)}{P(B)} & \mbox{if }P(B)>0\\
\mbox{undefined} & \mbox{if}P(B)=0
\end{cases}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Multiplication rule (MR)
\emph default
: rearranging the terms in the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $P(A\mid B)$
\end_inset

 we obtain the following equalities
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
P(A\cap B) & = & \begin{cases}
P(B)P(A\mid B) & \mbox{if }P(B)\neq0\\
P(A)P(B\mid A) & \mbox{if }P(A)\neq0\\
0 & \mbox{otherwise}
\end{cases}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

