\begin_layout Standard
If the probability of the occurrence of an event 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 does not change regardless of whether event 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 has occured, we are likely to conclude that the two events are independent.
 Formally we have the following definition.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(Independent events).
 We define two events 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 to be independent if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P(A\cap B)=P(A)P(B).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Remarks
\emph default
: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Do not confuse indepent events with mutually exclusive (disjoint) events.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 are mutually exclusive events, then 
\begin_inset Formula $A\cap B=\emptyset$
\end_inset

, which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $P(A\cap B)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Now, if they are independent as well, then 
\begin_inset Formula $P(A)=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $P(B)=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If an event 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is independent of itself, that is, if 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 are independent, then 
\begin_inset Formula $P(A)=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $P(A)=1$
\end_inset

.
 Why? Try to prove it!
\end_layout

